From Wikipedia: &quot;In 1916, Sheet and Tube workers at the East Youngstown plant rioted during a strike over working conditions, which resulted in most of the town's business district being burned to the ground. The strike was quelled by the arrival of National Guard troops&quot; 
<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Youngstown_Sheet_and_Tube" rel="nofollow">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Youngstown_Sheet_and_Tube</a>

From the New York Times of the day:
&quot;drink-crazed mobs ran riot, looting and burning property and causing tile loss of one life and financial loss amounting to $1,500,000,&quot;
&quot;East Youngstown has a popultion of 15,000 persons but only 400 are voters&quot;
<a href="http://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F00614F73C5D17738DDDA00894D9405B868DF1D3" rel="nofollow">query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F00614F73C5D17738...</a>

Strikers from Republic Iron and Steel Company and the Youngstown Sheet and Tube Company rioted, allegedly. From the NYT, it looks like heavily immigrant work force. From America's early union organizing (unionizing) labor history.
